\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the only definitive treatment for this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Liver transplantation","Ursodeoxycholic acid","Corticosteroids","Methotrexate","Colectomy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPrimary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC) is a chronic, progressive liver disease characterized by inflammation and fibrosis of intrahepatic and extrahepatic bile ducts. Currently, \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver transplantation\u003C/strong\u003E is the only definitive treatment for end-stage disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eursodeoxycholic acid\u003C/strong\u003E may improve liver biochemistry and symptoms, it has not been shown to improve survival or disease progression. \u003Cstrong\u003ECorticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Emethotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E have been studied but show no benefit in PSC. Although PSC is associated with inflammatory bowel disease, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolectomy\u003C/strong\u003E does not affect the progression of liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedical therapy focuses on managing complications such as pruritus, preventing bacterial cholangitis, and monitoring for cholangiocarcinoma. The median time from diagnosis to liver transplantation is 12-18 years.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC) is a progressive liver disease characterized by inflammation and scarring of bile ducts.","Liver transplantation is the only definitive treatment for end-stage PSC.","Medical therapies may help manage symptoms but do not alter disease progression."],"references":["Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31334972","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808","Rabiee A, Silveira MG. Primary sclerosing cholangitis. Transl Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2021 Apr 5;6:29. doi: 10.21037/tgh-20-266. PMID: 33824933; PMCID: PMC7829069"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46486"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15319"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46486"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-14T20:21:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T11:06:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8010"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61039"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"